events.summary: Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart was born on January 27, 1756, in Salzburg, Austria. He arrived in the world ready to compose, much to the bemusement of his father, who was still trying to figure out how to keep the violin in tune.

At the tender age of five, Mozart started composing and even strummed out some melodies that left his father scratching his head. One can only imagine Leopold thinking, 'Wait, I just taught him to play, and now he's writing his own tunes?'

Between 1762 and 1765, Mozart went on a grand tour of Europe with his family, performing as a child prodigy. This was much like today's talent shows, except the judges were kings and the prize was more royal court appearances!

Mozart composed his first symphony at the age of eight.  This piece was mostly dictated to his father, which probably resembled a father-son 'who's the boss' battle with a bit of music notation thrown in.

In 1770, Mozart's opera 'Mitridate, re di Ponto' premiered in Milan, paving the way for his illustrious career in opera. Thank goodness he didn't go with the original title, 'The King Who Can't Decide What to Wear,' which just doesn’t sing!

After returning from Italy in 1773, Mozart was employed as a court musician in Salzburg, but wasn’t quite feeling the love. His annual royalties were more 'pocket change' than 'pocket symphonies,' causing him to rethink his life choices.

In 1777, Mozart packed his bags and headed to Paris, eager for new opportunities but faced a slew of rejections, financial woe, and even drama from his mother’s illness. Paris might be known for love, but it didn’t quite return the feelings this time!

After much turmoil, Mozart returned to Salzburg in 1779. It's like trying to escape a small town only to realize you left your favorite socks behind.  Alas, his love-hate relationship with Salzburg wasn't over yet.

In 1781, Mozart enjoyed considerable success with the premiere of his opera 'Idomeneo.'  The folks in Vienna took notice, and he started to feel like the star in a musical where everyone finally remembered his name!

In his final years, Mozart crafted some of his most famous works. With operas like 'The Magic Flute,' it was as if he was on a creative caffeine high—spinning tunes left and right as if it was the last round of a musical trivia game!

Mozart's first encounter with Emperor Joseph II was like a blind date, but instead of awkward small talk, he dazzled the emperor with his musical talents, which eventually led to a supportive relationship. Who knew impressing royalty could be that melodious?

After a series of disputes, Mozart received an unforgettable exit from his archbishop, who literally gave him a kick in the backside. This graceful dismissal marked the beginning of Mozart's journey into freelancing, and let's be honest, it was a punchline in his career story.

events.event: Completion of 'Die Entführung aus dem Serail'
events.summary: Mozart completed his opera 'Die Entführung aus dem Serail', which became a hit faster than a rabbit in a magic hat. The opera spread like wildfire through Europe, cementing his status as a top-tier composer.

Mozart’s marriage to Constanze Weber was like a heated plot twist: first, there was jealousy over calf-measuring games and family drama, but in a shocking turn of events, they tied the knot in St. Stephen's Cathedral, proving that love conquers all (even maternal threats!).

Mozart met fellow composer Joseph Haydn, and together they created a buddy comedy duo of classical music. Haydn raved about Mozart, calling him the greatest composer known to him, likely leaving Mozart grinning from ear to ear.

Mozart became a Freemason, joining a secret society that valued friendship, morality, and the occasional catchy tune. His Masonic membership added a new layer of intrigue to his life, and his compositions even gained an esoteric flair.

The premiere of 'Le nozze di Figaro' was a grand success, except for a few audience members probably scratching their heads at the musical complexity. The opera became a sensational hit in Prague, making Mozart the toast of the town, one aria at a time.

Mozart's new part-time gig as the Imperial Chamber Composer came with some perks—though, sadly, the pay was akin to pocket change for his extraordinary talents. It kept a roof over his head during tough times, and composing dance music looked good on a resume.

In a year buzzing with creativity, Mozart completed 'The Magic Flute', a work filled with whimsy and adventure, almost as if he channeled the spirit of a playful child. It became one of his most beloved operas—surprise, surprise!

Mozart's final creative surge was like fitting all his best moves into the last dance of a party. He composed iconic pieces including 'Ave verum corpus' and the unfinished 'Requiem', leaving behind a legacy that remains unforgettable. What a glorious exit!

events.event: Public Success of The Magic Flute
events.summary: Mozart had a blast watching audiences enjoy his opera, The Magic Flute. It was like throwing a grand party where everyone brought their best dance moves, and he couldn't be more thrilled to see the applause pouring in, proving he could pull off a hit between writing checks to pay off his debts.

events.event: Premiere of La clemenza di Tito
events.summary: Traveling to Prague, Mozart conducted the premiere of La clemenza di Tito, written for a royal hoedown. Performing while feeling under the weather, he surely hoped no one would notice his sneezes between musical notes.

events.event: Premiere of the Little Masonic Cantata
events.summary: On November 17, Mozart threw another musical soirée with the premiere of the Little Masonic Cantata K. 623. It was a delightful gathering where everyone left humming tunes, and possibly scratching their heads about Masonic secret handshakes during intermission.

Mozart’s final days involved more than just completing his Requiem; it was a real-life drama filled with tender moments and a few too many ‘what's for dinner’ arguments with his wife. As he focused on music while reminding himself that maybe eating too many pastries wasn’t the best choice, the world held its breath.

On a seemingly calm evening, Mozart passed away, leaving behind a legacy that could fill concert halls for centuries. His exit was less of a dramatic curtain fall and more of an unscheduled intermission, as many pondered how a man so vibrant could leave the stage so suddenly.

Mozart was interred in a common grave, which sounds less like a place of rest and more like a location for a legendary jam session gone too soon. Though the attendance was a bit low for the funeral, it was all in line with the 'no frills' style of Viennese burials, where every musician's final gig was a quiet one.

events.event: Travel to Vienna to study with Mozart
events.summary: Young Beethoven traveled to Vienna with the hopes of learning from the legendary Mozart. Unfortunately, Mozart was probably too busy composing to take on students, but Beethoven likely made a lasting impression anyway, probably turning his head with those intense piano solos.

Beethoven was deeply influenced by Mozart's compositions while growing up. He even performed some of Mozart's operas in Bonn, likely multiple times, leading to a lifelong admiration that would inspire many of Beethoven's own works, which is kind of like shadowing a rock star without ever getting a backstage pass.

Beethoven took to composing cadenzas for Mozart's D minor piano concerto, showcasing his respect and admiration. It’s like bringing a fancy decoration to a party that wasn’t yours in the first place, but still trying to make it your own.

At the tender age of five, Mozart decided to wow the world with his musical talent, playing the clavier in public, probably leaving the audience wondering if he was a child prodigy or just very short for his age.

Mozart and his family embarked on a whirlwind tour through Italy, charming nobility with his compositions. It's rumored that he even picked up a few culinary tips along the way – pasta al dente was a highlight!

events.event: Award of the Papal Equestrian Order
events.summary: The Pope decided to honor Mozart with a shiny award, making him feel quite important, as if he needed another reason to compose glorious music.

events.event: Premier of The Marriage of Figaro
events.summary: Mozart's hilarious opera, filled with twists and turns, finally graced the stage, proving that love and mischief make for the best entertainment – even if some audience members might have been more confused than amused.
Mozart unveiled his whimsical masterpiece, The Magic Flute, leaving audiences enchanted. One can only assume it involved lots of flute jokes, which he would have found too punny to resist!
